{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"2cd6d17747254a124e2f41c8b65fd8c0e64c1a9ffc6fe38a65499558a0c4b5f0","slug":"pages.m09-sample-spaces-and-events-1-of-2","location":"/pages/099-m09-sample-spaces-and-events-1-of-2.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Sample Spaces and Events (1 of 2)","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"Shawn Wiggins","given":"Shawn","family":"Wiggins"},"name":"Shawn Wiggins","affiliations":["City College of San Francisco"],"id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0"}],"license":{"content":{"id":"CC-BY-4.0","url":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","name":"Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International","free":true,"CC":true}},"affiliations":[{"id":"City College of San Francisco","name":"City College of San Francisco"}],"numbering":{"title":{"offset":2}},"exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"099-m09-sample-spaces-and-events-1-of-2.md","url":"/textbook/build/099-m09-sample-space-117bd5e49418f8f7981b1654d3fb76a9.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Learning Objectives","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"iAkmtQ1pM3"}],"key":"sKMyOPsYx3"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"- Determine the sample space of a given random experiment.","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":4,"column":1}},"key":"vUoUdqNy77"}],"key":"i3oYXuBww9"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"As we saw in the previous module, probability questions arise when we are faced with a situation that involves uncertainty. Such a situation is called a ","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"SlQ1vggo3H"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"random experiment","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"hXikyFTN7c"}],"key":"DTUMdUp1fh"},{"type":"text","value":", an experiment that produces an outcome that cannot be predicted in advance (hence the uncertainty).","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"wdefJFihJf"}],"key":"pmrafkMVaF"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Here are a few examples of random experiments:","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"ana8Hqgo7Z"}],"key":"vtcUHhXGj8"},{"type":"list","ordered":true,"start":1,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":44,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Toss a coin once and\nrecord whether you get heads (H) or tails (T). The possible\noutcomes that this random experiment can produce are: {H, T}.","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":11,"column":1}},"key":"tPNXVzzNNI"}],"key":"zWDaVCgQRq"}],"key":"IifjirfzcV"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1},"end":{"line":15,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Toss a coin twice. The possible outcomes that this random experiment can produce are: {HH, HT,\nTH, TT}.","position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1},"end":{"line":14,"column":1}},"key":"HMwb0tT1pG"}],"key":"bKdylZBfdw"}],"key":"Giv9zL9y6i"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Toss a coin 3\ntimes. The possible outcomes in this case are: {HHH, THH, HTH, HHT, HTT, THT,\nTTH, TTT}.","position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":16,"column":1}},"key":"FyU6t4rmip"}],"key":"SO4NV89bJj"}],"key":"aJjz4tYeHs"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":31,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Toss a coin until you get the first\ntails\n(T). When we conduct this\nexperiment,\none possible outcome is that we get T in the first toss and we are done. Another\npossible outcome is that we get H in the first toss, toss a second time, get T\nand be done. We might need three tosses until we get the first T, etc. The\npossible outcomes of this random experiment are therefore: {T, HT, HHT, HHHT,\n...}. (Note that in this example the list of possible outcomes is not finite as\nin examples\n1-3.\nThis is not an important distinction at this point, just a noteworthy\nobservation.)","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"key":"OFKxKFu6HA"}],"key":"IejbnAp4Mi"}],"key":"G5oUyDg69t"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":32,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Choose a person at random and check\nhis or\nher blood type. In this random experiment the possible\noutcomes are the four blood types: {A, B, AB, O}.","position":{"start":{"line":32,"column":1},"end":{"line":32,"column":1}},"key":"uG0adMmHGu"}],"key":"uskU0Qmu6j"}],"key":"GecLkbPaxT"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":36,"column":1},"end":{"line":44,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"There are two job openings for a staff position at a certain college, and 4 equally qualified\ncandidates for the job (Ann, Beth,\nJim\nand Dan). For fairness, the human resources department decides to choose two of\nthe four candidates at random. The possible outcomes of this random experiment\nare all possible pairs of candidates: { (Ann, Beth), (Ann, Jim), (Ann, Dan),\n(Beth,\nJim), (Beth, Dan), (Jim, Dan) }.","position":{"start":{"line":36,"column":1},"end":{"line":36,"column":1}},"key":"s4wFQu1v54"}],"key":"yNm08d7Xvl"}],"key":"iliPkhKq1r"}],"key":"PyhryUTm7J"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Comment: Does Order Matter?","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"key":"h585HxZgUc"}],"identifier":"comment-does-order-matter","label":"Comment: Does Order Matter?","html_id":"comment-does-order-matter","implicit":true,"key":"EPss87ItX6"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note that when a coin is tossed twice, as in example 2, the possible outcome HT (indicating that the first toss was H and the second T) is NOT the same as the outcome TH (indicating that T occurred first and then H), and therefore both outcomes were listed separately. This is an example of a situation when order does matter. However, order does not always matter. Example 6 is a case in which order does not matter. The outcome (Ann, Beth) indicates that Ann and Beth are the two randomly chosen to get the jobs. Whether Ann appears first or Beth does is irrelevant in this case, and therefore (Beth, Ann) was ","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"key":"LVIpJbnTx9"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"not","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"key":"EoByMPfXzD"}],"key":"vqUzqO4awg"},{"type":"text","value":" listed as a separate outcome.","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"key":"LIDSyJ4yFJ"}],"key":"l1nBoYn8ee"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":49,"column":1},"end":{"line":49,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"There is really no rule that dictates when order matters and when it doesn’t. It is sometimes clear from the way the random experiment is defined. For example, suppose I were to change example 6 slightly:","position":{"start":{"line":49,"column":1},"end":{"line":49,"column":1}},"key":"z9piqv6hxA"}],"key":"Z1EoJ5Ga59"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"There are two job openings for similar staff positions at a certain college: one in the Registrar’s Office, and one in the Office of Admissions. The Human Resources Department has identified four equally qualified candidates for the jobs (Ann, Beth, Jim and Dan), and for fairness decides to choose two of the four candidates at random. The first chosen will fill the position in the Registrar’s Office, and the second will fill the position in the Office of Admissions.","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"key":"lcHcvxojn6"}],"key":"VmTLZHBdqH"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":53,"column":1},"end":{"line":53,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Now order ","position":{"start":{"line":53,"column":1},"end":{"line":53,"column":1}},"key":"uN797cpA31"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":53,"column":1},"end":{"line":53,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"is","position":{"start":{"line":53,"column":1},"end":{"line":53,"column":1}},"key":"pwqWXZBZgV"}],"key":"hOn2rzF4YB"},{"type":"text","value":" relevant—the two outcomes (Ann, Beth) and (Beth, Ann) are not the same in this scenario. The first outcome indicates that Ann got the position at the Registrar’s Office and Beth got the position at the Office of Admissions, while the second outcome indicates the reverse. In this case, therefore, all the possible outcomes are:","position":{"start":{"line":53,"column":1},"end":{"line":53,"column":1}},"key":"IzbOnNByGP"}],"key":"eb3OdS0z5b"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":55,"column":1},"end":{"line":55,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"{ (Ann, Beth), (Beth, Ann), (Ann, Jim), (Jim, Ann), (Ann, Dan), (Dan, Ann),","position":{"start":{"line":55,"column":1},"end":{"line":55,"column":1}},"key":"fLUTGs9PQD"}],"key":"nMZW7MKunj"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":57,"column":1},"end":{"line":57,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"(Beth, Jim), (Jim, Beth), (Beth, Dan), (Dan, Beth), (Jim, Dan), (Dan, Jim) }","position":{"start":{"line":57,"column":1},"end":{"line":57,"column":1}},"key":"Ux7s2jDbDd"}],"key":"owDukazvmQ"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":59,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Each random experiment has a set of possible outcomes, and there is ","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":59,"column":1}},"key":"enacbU5ugz"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":59,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"uncertainty","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":59,"column":1}},"key":"OuXOvrJCkD"}],"key":"CvxYFdWmNu"},{"type":"text","value":" as to which of the outcomes we are actually going to get once the experiment is conducted. This list of possible outcomes is called ","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":59,"column":1}},"key":"y8GTM2RSY7"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":59,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"the sample space","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":59,"column":1}},"key":"XLwTb05RQv"}],"key":"p8e9u9MYfc"},{"type":"text","value":" of the random experiment, and is denoted by the (capital) letter ","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":59,"column":1}},"key":"VxZ1MiFyqw"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":59,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"S.","position":{"start":{"li